    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4069809711" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4069809711" />
    <a title="Bobsie67" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1102847-bobsie67"><img alt="Bobsie67" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1214838737p2/1102847.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4069809711?book_show_action=true">Jul 05, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bobsie67" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bobsie67" href="/user/show/1102847-bobsie67">Bobsie67</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Audio CD 9781536607949" href="/book/show/31278112-memoirs-of-general-william-t-sherman">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1102847-bobsie67?shelf=audiobook">audiobook</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1102847-bobsie67?shelf=american-civil-war">american-civil-war</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1102847-bobsie67?shelf=military-strategy-war">military-strategy-war</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1102847-bobsie67?shelf=autobiography">autobiography</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1102847-bobsie67?shelf=memoir">memoir</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1102847-bobsie67?shelf=audio21">audio21</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4069809711" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8438285330267264833">Sherman is all business when recounting the civil war--who, what, when, where, how, and why. Lists of names and places seem to end all these chapters. He is more free when speaking about his time in California before the war, witnessing the madness of the 1849 gold rush, and his time as a banker. Sherman&apos;s &quot;March to the Sea,&quot; is rather gripping, and he explains his thoughts on total war as well as how his actions were part of Grant&apos;s grand strategy to wear the South down by defeating its armies </span>
  <span id="freeText8438285330267264833" style="display:none">Sherman is all business when recounting the civil war--who, what, when, where, how, and why. Lists of names and places seem to end all these chapters. He is more free when speaking about his time in California before the war, witnessing the madness of the 1849 gold rush, and his time as a banker. Sherman's "March to the Sea," is rather gripping, and he explains his thoughts on total war as well as how his actions were part of Grant's grand strategy to wear the South down by defeating its armies when possible, and to make life hard for those in rebellion so that the Southern armies would lose both moral and physical (food, arms, clothing) means of support. He supports his decisions by inserting many letters to and from his superiors. Sometimes this seems rather legalistic, but does give a good sense of what people in the army and government were thinking (and feeling--there was much pettiness, bickering, grandstanding, ego, and backstabbing to go around) at the time. Sometimes the level of detail is a bit exhausting, at least to me, who has read dozens of books on civil war battles, but still remain mostly a causal enthusiast.<br /><br />Sherman's prose is best when he chooses to reveal himself and breaks from giving "just the facts." I listened to the Audible version read by Bronson Pinchot, who does a very good job not to get bogged down by the numerous listings of people and places. At 35 hours--close to 1000 pages--this can seem long at times because of the level of detail recounted. Also, Sherman is best when giving opinions about various generals (his characterization, and interaction with, Confederate General Hood are priceless, as he is very witty here) and politicians (aside from Lincoln, basically hated them, especially Stanton). </span>
  <a data-text-id="8438285330267264833" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

